explanation:
For deciding if any part of OS_FileSys_FindVirtMountPoint is dead code you must know the data/layout and invariants the function relies on, and the routines that establish those invariants:

- OS_filesys_internal_record_t
  Needed to know the exact types and sizes of members accessed (flags and virtual_mountpt), e.g. the array type/size of virtual_mountpt and whether it is guaranteed NUL-terminated.

- OS_filesys_table
  The object table from which the filesys pointer is fetched; required to see initial/default contents and possible sentinel values.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET / OS_ObjectIndexFromToken
  The macro/lookup implementation that converts *token to a filesys pointer (or index). You must know whether it can return NULL, an invalid pointer, or always a valid record — this affects reachability of the function body and whether checks are redundant.

- OS_object_token_t
  The token type/semantics (and valid value ranges). Determines whether *token usage can be assumed valid or whether some checks are unnecessary.

- OS_FILESYS_FLAG_IS_MOUNTED_VIRTUAL
  The flag mask tested at the top. To determine if the flag test can ever be true/false in practice you need its definition and how/when it is set.

- OS_strnlen
  The exact behavior/implementation used (wrapper around strnlen or custom). The code relies on strnlen returning sizeof(...) when no NUL is found; to know whether the mplen >= sizeof(...) branch is reachable you need its semantics.

- strncmp
  Standard semantics are likely known, but include it to be explicit about comparison behavior and any wrappers that could change behavior (safety/locale/etc.).

- OS_FileSysAddFixedMap, OS_FileSysStartVolume_Impl, OS_FileSysMountVolume_Impl, OS_FileSys_Initialize
  The functions that initialize or modify entries in OS_filesys_table / virtual_mountpt and set the flags. Inspecting these shows whether virtual_mountpt is always NUL-terminated, whether it can be empty, and when the IS_MOUNTED_VIRTUAL flag is set/cleared — information required to decide if any branches/conditions in the target are impossible (and thus dead).

In short: to decide if any condition or entire branches in OS_FileSys_FindVirtMountPoint are redundant (dead code), you need the record layout and guarantees (types/sizes/termination), the table and lookup semantics that produce the filesys pointer, the flag definition and all writers/initializers that set virtual_mountpt and the flag, and the exact string helper semantics used.
